🧠 1. Full agent frameworks with MCP + memory/session support
Goose (Block’s open-source agent framework)
One of the most complete open-source stacks right now
Native MCP integration
Built-in:
Memory management (short + long-term context)
Multi-turn sessions
Tool orchestration
Extensible plugin/tool system

👉 This is one of the few frameworks explicitly designed to combine:

agent orchestration
MCP tools
persistent context

Microsoft Agent Framework (open-source)
Strong MCP support (first-class concept)
Supports:
Multiple MCP tools per agent
Tool discovery via MCP
Good for structured enterprise workflows

⚠️ Caveat:

Session/memory handling is not opinionated — you usually wire it yourself (e.g., storage layer, Redis, etc.)

OpenClaw (autonomous agent runtime)
Fully open-source autonomous agent
Has:
Persistent memory (filesystem-based)
Session-style execution via “gateway”
Tool definitions via config files
Can integrate external tools (including MCP-style setups)

👉 More “agent OS” than framework, but useful if you want:

long-running sessions
real task execution

🔧 2. MCP-native / MCP-first tooling frameworks
mcp-agent (MCP Stack)
Lightweight framework specifically for MCP agents
Lets you:
Define custom tools programmatically
Attach resources (DBs, APIs)
Configure memory systems (hybrid/working memory)

👉 Very close to what you asked for (custom tools + memory)

ACI.dev (tool-calling platform)
Open-source MCP-compatible platform
Connects hundreds of tools via MCP or function calling
Focus: tool ecosystem, not full session lifecycle

RAGFlow / Dify
Production-grade agent platforms
Support:
tool calling
workflows
memory (via RAG / pipelines)
MCP support is emerging or indirect

🧩 3. Supporting layers (for session + robustness)
Agent Lifecycle Toolkit (ALTK)
Middleware for:
validation
lifecycle hooks
tool-call safety
Can be combined with MCP agents

👉 Useful if you want production-grade session handling

⚠️ Important reality check (very relevant to your question)

Even though MCP standardizes tools, session + identity management is still weak across frameworks:

No standard “agent identity” across sessions
No built-in session tracking in MCP itself
Most frameworks implement sessions ad hoc

Example from real-world usage:

“There’s no persistent identity for agents across sessions… every agent is basically a stranger.”